  "opinion": "As a retired woman in Bari who has spent decades tending to her garden and watching the birds in the park, I’ve learned that the internet can be as unpredictable as a sudden storm. With so many hours spent daily on social media, it’s easy to become overwhelmed by the flood of information—especially when it comes to fake news. My anxiety often flares up when I see posts that seem too good to be true, like stories about miraculous cures or sudden financial windfalls. I’ve found that the best way to manage this is to slow down, much like I do when I’m pruning my rose bushes. First, I check the source carefully—just as I’d verify a recipe before baking, I look for reputable websites or trusted news outlets. I also limit my time on social media by setting specific times for checking messages, similar to how I schedule my gardening sessions. Another strategy is to share only what I know for sure, because I’ve seen how quickly misinformation can spread, just like weeds that take root in the garden. It’s important to be kind to oneself too—sometimes the anxiety is just a part of being human, and it’s okay to take a break and enjoy a cup of coffee while watching the sunset. Remember, in life, as in the garden, patience and care go a long way.",
